The paper discusses the design of a network architecture for enabling the Internet of Things in remote environments, which involves the coordination and planning of unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) to provide coverage to underlay devices and exploit device-to-device (D2D) communication. This work is related to the field of network infrastructure (cs.NI) and robotics (cs.RO) as it involves the deployment and coordination of UAVs. The paper also discusses the need for resilience in the network, which is related to the field of systems and control (cs.SY). Additionally, the paper mentions the potential for adversarial attacks, which is related to the field of cryptography and security (cs.CR). Finally, the paper proposes a feedback-based adaptive framework, which involves the use of machine learning and artificial intelligence techniques (cs.AI).
